# Report Content

The world is moving at an unprecedented pace and the India growth story train chugs along as it navigates new challenges in AI, semi conductors, consumer, healthcare among others. Other macro challenges like deglobalization, further focus on technological sovereignity, tariffs blur the path ahead. It is thus, important as investors to find the right sectors to invest in and back the winning horses. The winning startups will not just provided financial returns but also generate value that will help further build the nation. They will solve for sovereign infrastructure, build the artificial intelligence that powers our most critical sectors, and create the core intellectual property that underpins the entire technology stack, from data centers to semiconductor design. In doing so, they will not just build for India, but build for the world.

In this report we provide to you 5 sectors ripe for startups to build in and investments to follow. The sectors are namely, 

Aging Population Technology
Data centre Technologies
AI powered lending
AI powered Diagnostic
EDA and IP for semiconductors

There is a strong bias towards AI in this selection from an application layer (lending) to a foundation layer (data centres and semiconductors), this is because we believe AI to add significant value to the future wrt these industries in the application layer and they will need the foundation layer, thus creating a virtuous cycle. Thus, there is value created in both layers and entrepreneurs should create value in both. This is a diverse collection from the point of view of sectors chosen ranging from fintech to heathtech, yet common themes emerge as the analysis was conducted. A range of demographics have also been served from the senior citizens in eldercare to the gen z who expect consumer tech like AI and UX in their banking applications.

Thus these sectors cover a wide range of use cases and target demographics while also maintaining a strong bet on AI and its applications.

### Technology Enabled Startups in Eldercare

This sector encompasses technology first solutions to address the rising elderly population of the country through technologies like AI, IOT, digital health platforms and assistive technologies. We have decided to focus on pure tech plays to service this demographic rather than a broad thesis on elder care.

This sector encompasses use cases like smart home techonology for safety, fall detection, monitoring, communication software for elders to stay in touch with their children, software for healthcare management of elders and other technology enabled solutions that create scalable, data-driven approaches to eldercare challenges. Potential implementation for smart home tech can include solutions like voice assistant devices, iot devices - like lights, speakers, and security systems, fall detection systems that connect and act on the data collected and provide value to both the stakeholders - the elder and their children, solving in this sector is a 2 body problem, of the parent and child.

Remote health monitoring using Sensors, wearables, and IoT devices whicch track vitals, activity, sleep, fall risk, and medication adherence is another implementation of the same market opportunity.

The market opportunity is defined by the demographic itself, the elderly population will grow by 40% from 2021-31 as compared to 8% for the general population, this creates a huge market opportunity of **$13 billion by 2030**¬†focused on health, consumer goods, services, and discretionary spending. Adding to this the fact that technology has permeated the lives of senior citizens with 77% of urban seniors now having smartphones and using messaging apps like Whatsapp, with this percentage only likely to increase as the demographic widens. The market is further validated by the¬†**payer-user dynamic**¬†where 60-75% of eldercare company revenue comes from children purchasing technology solutions for their parents, representing a willing-to-pay customer base driven by guilt, worry, and trust concerns about parents' safety and wellbeing. This also shows that the products are to be marketed to a generation that has seen technology affect their lives positively and more likely to adopt technology first solutions.

There are multiple factors at play which can act as a catalyst for this sector, accelerated technology adoption, NRI diaspora growth and rise of nuclear families creating a need for technology first solutions to solve for the elderly members of the family. The¬†**baby boomer generation entering senior years**¬†- those born in the 1950s-60s who became affluent during India's economic development starting in the 1980s - now represents the first generation of tech-savvy, financially capable seniors with¬†**significant capacity to spend**.India's¬†**WOOPWHI segment**¬†(Well-off Older People Without Health Issues) represents the most lucrative early adopter base for technology solutions.

Thus **smart home technology, communication software, and healthcare management platforms**¬†represent the highest-value, most venture-scalable opportunities within the broader eldercare ecosystem.

### Data Center Technologies

Data centres are the¬†**digital backbone**¬†powering cloud services, AI workloads, edge applications, and regulated data hosting.¬† While large incumbents focus are expected to focus on large-scale facility construction and try to ride the waves of high demand brought upon by AI and modern computing, there are whitespaces for startups in technologies that enhance efficiency, sustainability and sovereign control. This could look like advanced cooling and thermal management solutions such as direct-to-chip liquid cooling, two-phase immersion systems which aim to reduce Power Usage Effectiveness by 10-25% and enable GPU dense racks for essential AI workflows that generate 20x more heat. AI driven operations platforms deliver predictive maintenance and real-time resource optimization which unlock 25-40% improvements in uptime and 15-20% energy savings.

India‚Äôs data-centre market is poised for a¬†**massive expansion,** from¬†**1.35 GW**¬†of installed capacity in 2025 to nearly¬†**5 GW by 2030 which will** require¬†**$20 billion**¬†in new data-hall capex and an additional¬†**$10 billion**¬†in equity financing to bridge the infrastructure gap. The core data-centre services market is forecast to grow from¬†**$10.1 billion in 2025**¬†to¬†**$21.8 billion by 2030**¬†at a¬†**16.6 percent CAGR**, driven by enterprise cloud adoption and digital-sovereignty mandates. Within this ecosystem, the¬†**cooling-technology segment,** is a¬†**$2.4 billion**¬†market in 2025 projected to reach¬†**$7.7 billion**¬†by 2030 at¬†**26.4 percent CAGR**, with each 1 percent PUE improvement saving roughly¬†**$50 million**¬†per 100 MW facility annually.¬†This goes to show that while data centres will primarly be a high capex sector, the savings provided by technological improvements are invaulable and should be of focus to startups in this space.

Two strong catalysts will speed this transition. Firstly, the¬†phenomenal growth of AI applications, supported by the IndiaAI mission's¬†‚Çπ10,372 crore¬†investment in 18,000 GPUs, is creating pressing needs for AI-compatible cooling, power supplies, and AIOps platforms that can handle compute loads that draw up to¬†20√ó¬†more power per rack. Secondly,¬†mandates for data sovereignty¬†under the Digital Personal Data Protection Act, the RBI regulations, and the introduction of a¬†National Data Centre¬†for sensitive government data sets require organizations to host data and AI models domestically, creating a whitespace for compliance-ready and sovereign-cloud infrastructure solutions. Individually and collectively, the trends create an interesting investment thesis in the space of delivering specialist efficiency, sustainability, and sovereignty technologies where leaner, innovative start-ups can outrun balance-sheet-weighted incumbents.

### AI in Lending

AI powered Lending represents the integration of AI and ML into the entire credit life cycle, from origination and underwriting to disbursal, monitoring and collections. While traditional credit relied on static credit histories, AI driven models are able to leverage alternate data sources including UPI transactions, GST returns, digital wallet activity among others. This creates access to credit for multiple unaccounted for segments: new to credit Gen Z consumers, MSMEs without collateral, gig workers and populations in tier 2 and tier 3 cities. This has also led to speeding up of credit disbursal from weeks to minutes ensuring greater customer satisfaction.

India‚Äôs digital lending market is experiencing explosive growth projected to reach **$515 billion by 2030**¬†from $38 billion in 2021, representing a CAGR of over 33%. The lending segment now commands the largest share of fintech funding in India, with¬†**$135 million invested in Q1 2025 alone**, surpassing payments and other categories. There also exists a vast credit demand of MSMEs who face a credit gap of **‚Çπ25-30 lakh crore**¬†($320-400 billion), with only 14% accessing formal finance. Over 70% of India's digitally-native Gen Z and millennial population prefer seamless, app-based banking experiences over traditional channels and are fueling adoption of instant personal loans, BNPL products, and embedded credit offerings.

Multiple interconnected forces make up the catalyst that will drive up the growth in AI powered lending. Firstly, it has emerged as the dominant vertical in fintech command the major proportion in funding reflecting investor conviction. Secondly,¬†the explosion of¬†**alternative data sources**, particularly UPI, has created an unparalleled credit assessment infrastructure. UPI processed¬†**over 20 billion transactions in August 2025**¬†with a monthly value exceeding¬†**‚Çπ24.85 lakh crore**, providing granular, real-time payment flows from platforms like PhonePe, Google Pay, and Paytm. The Account Aggregator framework, which crossed¬†**100 million consents**¬†and links¬†**2.2 billion financial accounts**, alongside the newly launched Unified Lending Interface (ULI), now allows lenders to access consent-based income, expense, GST, and property data instantly which eliminates documentation friction and enables ML models to assess borrowers with little or no credit history with unprecedented accuracy. The credit gap faced by MSMEs represents a massive opportunity to startups who can leverage this data and solve for these currently excluded sectors of the economy. Lastly, Gen Z which prefers instant validation expects a similar experience in banking and credit, expect long processing times and clunky UI to be a thing of the past as AI native and cosumer tech like UI takes over and offers the same e-commerce like conveneince to this generation.

### AI Powered Diagnostics

AI-Powered Diagnostics represents the application of artificial intelligence, machine learning, and computer vision technologies to enhance the accuracy, speed, and accessibility of medical diagnosis in India.  AI-Powered Diagnostics encompasses two strategic layers where startups can build competitive advantage. The¬†**Data Layer**¬†addresses healthcare‚Äôs foundational challenge of fragmented data by integrating lab reports, medical images, electronic health records, wearable device streams, and historical patient information into secure, interoperable, AI-ready datasets that comply with India‚Äôs Digital Personal Data Protection Act (2023). The¬†**Application Layer**¬†leverages these datasets to train and deploy diagnostic models that autonomously analyze images, lab values, and clinical histories to detect disease signatures, flag abnormalities, and generate evidence-based insights. These AI models act as a ‚Äúsecond eye‚Äù for physicians, augmenting rather than replacing clinical expertise. When embedded within telemedicine platforms and diagnostic-centre workflows, they extend specialist-level diagnostics to underserved areas. Crucially, scaling AI-enabled testing centres and diagnostic infrastructure delivers far greater reach than training additional specialists, offering a practical solution to India‚Äôs chronic shortage of doctors as scaling for data will prove to be easier as cloud enabled wearables and solutions come to the forefront and thus will be a more swift solution than waiting for decades for a new genration of doctors.
 

AI expenditure in India's healthcare sector reached USD 665 million in 2018 and is expected to reach USD 11.78 billion by 2025, with AI contributing an estimated USD 1 trillion to India's economy by 2035. The global AI in healthcare market was valued at USD 11 billion in 2021 and is forecasted to reach USD 188 billion by 2030. This growth is underpinned by severe structural deficits: approximately 70% of healthcare facilities are situated in urban areas where only 30% of the population resides, while only 33% of doctors serve two-thirds of the population in rural areas. This emphasizes the demand-supply mis match faced and thus serves as a whitespace for startups to build in.

### EDA and IP in Semiconductors

**Electronic Design Automation (EDA) and Intellectual Property (IP)**¬†represent the critical upstream segment of the semiconductor value chain, forming the foundation for all chip design activities. EDA tools are sophisticated software platforms that enable engineers to design, simulate, verify, and validate semiconductor circuits before fabrication. IP cores are pre-designed, reusable functional blocks such as processor cores, memory controllers, interface protocols, and analog circuits that can be integrated into System-on-Chip (SoC) designs to accelerate development and reduce costs.

India's semiconductor market is projected to grow from $52 billion (2024) to $100-110 billion by 2030 (18% CAGR), with the global EDA IP market expanding from $12.25 billion (2024) to $22.34 billion by 2033. Application-specific drivers include: automotive semiconductors rising from $312 per ICE vehicle to $600 per EV as India targets 30% EV penetration by 2030.  India now hosts 100+ semiconductor startups with VC investment surging 5.6x from $5 million (2023) to $28 million (2024), though only 34% work on proprietary IP versus 65.5% in services,indicating substantial whitespace for IP-focused ventures. Even indigenizing chips for just 10% of India's 150 million annual smartphone market (15-18 million units) creates compelling commercial rationale for domestic IP.

India‚Äôs semiconductor design ecosystem is at an inflection point, driven by the convergence of policy support, global realignment, and investor confidence. The Design Linked Incentive (DLI) Scheme,covering up to 50% of design costs (‚Çπ15 crore cap) and offering 4-6% of sales support over five years (‚Çπ30 crore cap),has enabled 278 institutions and 72 startups to access industry-grade EDA tools and IP cores, while government validation through DLI approval has already helped 10 of 23 projects secure Series A funding. India is also exploring China‚Äôs 80% mask-set subsidy model, which previously fostered over 3,300 design firms. Geopolitical tailwind from  China+1 diversification is accelerating talent and creating exit opportunities: AMD, NXP, and Qualcomm are expanding to 3,000, 6,000, and 14,000 engineers respectively, prompting experienced professionals to launch IP startups, while MNCs increasingly acqui-hire local design firms for talent and technology. Simultaneously, Western fabless companies, incentivized by the US and EU Chips Acts, are turning to India for trusted design partnerships in automotive, defense, and industrial segments. The deep-tech capital landscape has also transformed, with the India Deep Tech Investment Alliance committing $1 billion over the next decade and 92% of investors expressing optimism,63% willing to fund long-gestation, IP-led ventures. This new wave of confidence is reflected in major rounds such as Netrasemi‚Äôs ‚Çπ107 crore Series A (edge AI SoCs), Mindgrove‚Äôs ‚Çπ85 crore (RISC-V), and AGNIT‚Äôs $3.5 million seed (GaN power), signaling that India‚Äôs EDA and IP design ecosystem is rapidly maturing into a globally competitive innovation hub.
